Task 3/3 a

probYplus1 <- function(x1,x2)
{
  px1 = 1/16*exp(-(x1^2+x2^2)/32)
  px2 = exp(-(x1^2+x2^2)/2)
  return(px1/(px1+px2))
}
probYminus1 <- function(x1,x2)
{
  px1 = 1/16*exp(-(x1^2+x2^2)/32)
  px2 = exp(-(x1^2+x2^2)/2)
  return(px2/(px1+px2))
}

Now, really, the linear kernel is able to produce error 0.125 with cost level 100. This is because x squared becomes positive for all x AND the results is smaller than x with x < 1 and it bigger if x > 1. For x.1 with mean = 0 & var = 1, it is more likely that x is close to zero AND for x.2 with mean = 0 & var = 16 it is more likely to be more than 1. This is why the model is better able to separate the two sets now as can be seen from the model graph created without the linear xs.
